04622nam a22007215i 9780271082936DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20182018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710829367 a10.1515/97802710829362doi  a(DE-B1597)584309  a(OCoLC)1266229079  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLAN0150002bisacsh1 aStillion Southard, Belinda A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation. How to Belong :bWomen’s Agency in a Transnational World /cBelinda A. Stillion Southard. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Rhetorics of Belonging in a Transnational World -- t1 Belonging as Denizenship: Peace Women and Regional Dwelling -- t2 Belonging as Cosmopolitanism: Ellen Johnson Sirleaf’s New Nationalism -- t3 Belonging as Connectivity: Michelle Bachelet’s Transnational Governance -- tConclusion: How to Belong (or Not) to the Nation-State -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn How to Belong, Belinda Stillion Southard examines how women leaders throughout the world have asserted their rhetorical agency in troubling economic, social, and political conditions. Rather than utilizing the concept of citizenship to bolster political influence, the women in the case studies presented here rely on the power of relationships to create a more habitable world.With the rise of global capitalism, many nation-states that have profited from invigorated flows of capital have also responded to the threat of increased human mobility by heightening national citizenship’s exclusionary power. Through a series of case studies that include women grassroots protesters, a woman president, and a woman United Nations director, Stillion Southard analyzes several examples of women, all as embodied subjects in a particular transnational context, pushing back against this often violent rise in nationalist rhetoric. While scholars have typically used the concept of citizenship to explain what it means to belong, Stillion Southard instead shows how these women have reimagined belonging in ways that have enabled them to create national, regional, and global communities.As part of a broader conversation centered on exposing the violence of national citizenship and proposing ways of rejecting that violence, this book seeks to provide answers through the powerful rhetorical practices of resilient and inspiring women who have successfully negotiated what it means to belong, to be included, and to enact change beyond the boundaries of citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aEllen Johnson Sirleaf.  aLiberia.  aMichelle Bachelet.  aTransnational.  aUN Women.  abelonging.  afeminism.  arhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108293640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271082936423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271082936/original  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK